text: SYNLETT0936-52141437-2096 © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York 2017, 28, A–F letter en Intramolecular Photoredox Reaction of Naphthoquinone Deriva- tives Yoshio Ando  Takashi Matsumoto1  Keisuke Suzuki* Department of Chemistry, Tokyo Institute of Technology,  2-12-1 O-okayama, Meguro-ku, Tokyo 152-8551, Japan ksuzuki@chem.titech.ac.jp We  report  herein  a  unique  photoreaction  of  naphtho- quinones, which could be regarded as an intramolecular re- dox reaction (Scheme 1): the benzylic position in I becomes oxidized, while the quinone moiety is reduced into the hy- droquinone level to give oxacycle II. The study originated from a discovery in our total syn- thesis2 of the pluramycin-class antibiotics3,4 (Scheme 2). In a  model  study,  naphthalene  1a  was  oxidized  with  ceri- um(IV) ammonium nitrate (CAN). Quinone 2a, thus formed, turned out to be unexpectedly labile, giving product 3a. The latter  conversion  was  induced  by  the  ambient  light  in  the laboratory.  After  optimization,  the  yield  became  quantita- tive. The key points were (1) separation of the steps for not exposing  acid-labile  3a  to  the  acidic  media  of  CAN  oxida- Received: 24.02.2017 Accepted after revision: 22.03.2017 Published online: 19.04.2017 DOI: 10.1055/s-0036-1589001; Art ID: st-2017-u0139-l Abstract  Photoinduced intramolecular redox reaction of naphthoqui- none derivatives is described, enabling C–H bond oxygenation at the α- position of the quinone nucleus and the quinone reduction under pho- toirradiation. The substrate scope and mechanistic insight are reported.

Key words  naphthoquinone, photochemistry, redox reaction, cycliza- tion, C–H bond functionalization Scheme 1   Photoredox reaction intramolecular redox reaction © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–F tion, and (2) exclusion of O2 at step 2 for avoiding possible side reactions.4,5 The following procedure is representative: Naphthalene 1a (21.7 mg, 71.8 μmol) in MeCN (1 mL) was treated with CAN (84.3 mg, 154 μmol) in H2O (0.3 mL) at 0 °C in a brown flask  (otherwise,  the  redox  reaction  already  starts  by  the room  light  during  the  oxidation).  After  the  oxidation  was complete  in  ten  minutes,  the  products  were  extracted (EtOAc,  brown  separatory  funnel)  and  concentrated  in  a brown  flask.  The  crude  material  2a  was  transferred  as EtOAc solution into an ordinary glass flask covered by alu- minum foil, concentrated in vacuo, and flushed with argon. After dissolved in MeCN (7 mL) and degassed by sonication, the solution was exposed to room light (32 W, fluorescent light) under argon at room temperature for four hours. Con- centration  in  vacuo  followed  by  purification  by  flash  col- umn chromatography (SiO2) gave 3a (19.1 mg, 97%).6 Early  reports  on  such  photoredox  reactions  can  be found in the chemistry of natural naphtho-7 and benzoqui- nones,8 where a formyl or methoxy appendage is oxidized at the expense of the quinone oxidation level. Mechanisti- cally,  Baldwin’s  proposal  via  radical  →  zwitterionic  spe- cies7a  has  been  adopted  to  these  reactions7  and  also  to those of anthraquinones.9 Scheme 2   Unexpected photoredox reaction

Upon light irradiation, quinone 2 under- goes  n–π*  excitation  to  form  exited  state  A  (step  1). Norrish-type II intramolecular 1,5-hydrogen shift forms bi- radical B (step 2).10,11 Intramolecular electron transfer gen- erates zwitterion C (step 3), which is trapped by the proxi- mal phenol to give the product 3 (steps 4 and 5).12 In view of the potential utility of the process in organic synthesis,  enabling  facile  C–H  functionalization  in  the  vi- cinity of quinone nucleus, we decided to undertake a study to clarify the scope and limitation and also to gain mecha- nistic insight. Naphthalenes 1b–i with different α-substituents, R and R′, were prepared by conventional methods (see Supporting Information), and used as the precursors to quinones 2b–i (Table  1).  According  to  the  procedure  stated  above,  naph- thalenes  1b–i  were  oxidized  with  CAN,  and  the  resulting quinones 2b–i were immediately subjected to the photore- actions and the results are summarized in Table 1.13,14 The key observations are as follows. Entry 1: Quinone 2a with a tetrahydropyran was initial- ly prepared as a model compound for aryl C-glycoside syn- thesis,2 and the behavior has been described above. Entry  2:  Quinone  2b  with  a  formyl  group  gave  lactone 3b in an excellent yield, although a longer time (20 h) was required.7b,c

Entry  3:  Quinone  2c  with  a  1,3-dioxane  ring  gave  the corresponding spiro-orthoester 3c in 52% yield. In addition, lactone  3b  was  obtained  in  25%  yield,  which  could  be  ex- plained in the following way. Acetals 1c and 2c were labile to acidic conditions of the CAN oxidation even at low tem- perature (–20 °C). The hydrolyzed product 2b,15 partly pro- duced, was converted into lactone 3b. Scheme 3   Postulated mechanism © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–F Entry 4: Quinone 2d with a methoxymethyl group gave the corresponding product 3d in 93% yield in four hours, il- lustrating  applicability  to  the  substrates  with  acyclic  sub- stituent. Entry  5:  Substrate  2e  with  a  tetraline  ring  underwent the photoredox reaction in 20 hours to give spiroether 3e in excellent yield. The reacting C–H bond is located at a ben- zylic position. Entries 6–9: Quinones 2f and 2g had six- and five-mem- bered carbocycles. In both cases, the photoredox reactions completed  within  seven  hours,  giving  spiro-ethers  3f  and 3g  in  excellent  yields.  Note  that  substrates 2f  and  2g  have tertiary C–H bonds. By contrast, substrates 2h and 2i with lesser degrees of alkyl substitution showed a limitation. Al- though oxidations of 1h and 1i uneventfully gave quinones 2h and 2i, which gave no expected products 3h and 3i, even after a long-time exposure to light, and only decomposition was observed.16

In  relation  to  the  mechanistic  framework  (Scheme  3), these  results  on  the  effects  of  substituents  R,  R′  suggested the  importance  of  two  related,  but  sometimes  dichotomic factors. Hydrogen abstraction (step 2; A → B): Of primary signif- icance  is  the  ease  of  the  hydrogen  abstraction.  Figure  1 shows pertinent bond-dissociation energy (BDE) for the C– H bonds of the parent methane derivatives III having sub- stituents, R and R′.17 Based on these BDE data, the hydrogen abstraction would be easy for substrates 2a–e by the pres- ence of one or two oxygen(s) or a phenyl group. As for the alkyl-substituted  substrates  2f–i,  two  alkyl  groups  are needed: quinones 2f and 2g with tertiary C–H bonds were good substrates, while quinones 2h and 2i with secondary and primary C–H bonds were not.11c electron- whithdrawing group Scheme 4   Substrate 2j with a cyano group . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C Table 1   Photoredox Reaction of Naphthoquinones © Georg Thieme Verlag  Stuttgart · New York — Synlett 2017, 28, A–F . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

Electron transfer (step 3; B → C): As an additional factor, substituent effect on the electron-transfer step must also be important.9a  Scheme  4  shows  a  telling  example  of  cyano- substituted quinone 2j. Even though the BDE of C–H bond next to a cyano group is virtually the same as that next to a methoxy group (see Figure 1), the photoreaction of 2j only led to decomposition, which may be ascribed to retardation of the electron-transfer step by a cyano group.12,18 Finally, two interesting examples are described. Scheme 5  shows  quinone  2k  with  a  cyclopropylmethyl  group,  giv- ing 3k in 61% yield, retaining the cyclopropyl ring intact.19,20 Notably,  a  cyclopropylmethyl  substituent  (sec-C–H  bond) allowed a clean reaction (cf. 2h, a poor substrate in Table 1 and also see Figure 1). We have described an intramolecular photoredox reac- tion  of  naphthoquinones,  providing  an  approach  to  an  in- teresting  class  of  compounds  3,  which  are  generally  inac- cessible due to acid/base sensitivity. The  present  method  would  find  broad  application  in complex molecule synthesis.21 Further studies are currently ongoing in our laboratory.
